postcontent:
Cell = REDACTED; will do $3000 for everything!
•	Nagant Revolver: $400. 1938 Tula arsenal refurb. Wood grips, comes with holster and lanyard. Early import with discreet import marks under the barrel. Comes with 34 boxes of milsurp ammo (476 rounds). I have done a little work on the spring to lighten the trigger pull. 
•	Romanian Tokarev Pistol: $550. 1953 dated pistol, great bluing, shoots great. Comes with leather military holster and 2 original mags. Comes with around 1,000 rounds of military surplus ammo packed in 72 round boxes. 
•	Antique Vest Pocket Pistol: $175. Single shot, nickel plated wood grips, .22 short caliber. Wood grips are perfect, some pitting throughout but functionally great. Comes with around 30 rounds of .22 shorts. I have fired this gun and it works. 
•	French Berthier Rifle: $500. Nothing wrong or missing. Handguard wobbles a bit from side to side but nothing major. This is the earlier 3-shot version of the rifle. Many were later converted to 5-shot versions. It comes with an early bayonet with zinc handle. Later bayonets had a brass handle. The bayonet is in great shape, with a scabbard in equally great shape. This rifle fires 8mm Lebel ammo from Mannlicher-style clips. This rifle comes with 4 of those clips, newly manufactured by a company in Australia; they function perfectly. Original clips are ridiculously expensive when you can find them. Includes a box of 8mm Lebel ammo.
•	Bullets for Reloading

x3: Hornady A-Max 6.5mm .264” 100 gr. bullets, 100 ct. ($25 each)

•	Japanese Arisaka Type 99: $500. 1941-produced rifle. Great rifling, chromed bore. Intact aerial rear sights. Defaced mum. Comes with Hornady die set, 1 box of Norma 174 gr. round nose bullets, 3 boxes of Hornady 150 gr. bullets, and around 120 pieces of PPU 7.7 Jap brass. 
•	1851 Colt Navy Revolver: $50. This gun is complete, but taken apart and needs refinishing. Includes everything to make a full pistol, including all the main parts and guts of the gun, save for one leaf spring that broke. Just needs to be refinished and I don’t have the time. 
•	H&R .38 S&W Top Break Revolver: $320 Good condition revolver, nickel plated with black rubber grips. Grips are perfect and not chipped. Nickel plating is very nice, Rifling in barrel is great, a bit of pitting in barrel. Comes with Lee die set, 30 rounds of black powder ammo, around that many cleaned cases, and about 350-400 lead bullets. 
•	VERY RARE Japanese VZ24 Mauser Rifle w/ Original Sling: $700. This VZ24 Mauser rifle was made in Czechoslovakia for the Imperial Japanese Navy. It is in great condition, bluing is good and so is the bore/rifling. Comes complete with the original cleaning rod. This rifle is NOT import marked anywhere, likely a veteran bring-back from WW2, although I do not have documentation. The receiver ring has no crest, only the date of 1937. The side of the receiver reads “CESKOSLOVENSKA ZBROJOVKA, A.S., BRNO” with “V.Z. 24” below it. The bolt serial number does not match the receiver. The serial number on the receiver and stock match, but the stock serial number has a “C” prefix. C and P prefix serial numbers are indicative of Japanese use. The jury is out as to what the serial number prefixes mean. Some say the P-prefix rifles were made for China (which were subsequently intercepted and used by the IJN), while those with C prefix were made for Japan. Others say that the C and P prefixes represented which Czech factory made the rifle. Most Japanese-used VZ24’s you see will exhibit the P-prefix serial number, but research indicates that C-serial numbered rifles were used by the Japanese as well. The NRA museum agrees with me, see the link below. The only way to tell for sure if the rifle was used by the Japanese is the presence of capture papers from WW2 or a sling marked with Japanese Kanji letters. This rifle has the original sling marked with Kanji letters, which are white and vibrant. Placing a value on this rare rifle is difficult as not many are offered for sale. Rock Island Auction estimates the price of a P-prefix rifle that is missing the cleaning rod and sling to go for $950-$1600. See link below. While I think this price is a bit optimistic, it indicates that this is no ordinary run-of-the-mill VZ24 rifle. My price is $700. Reasonable offers will be entertained. I prefer to deal locally, but can bend. Don’t miss this opportunity to add a very rare Mauser rifle variant to your collection!
